The virtual room is a means of creating large areas consisting of many
similar looking rooms, without coding a separate .c file for each room.

To do this, the grid needs a daemon to control it and a set of files that
describe the rooms. You may have a different description for each room
in the grid, or share descriptions amongst the rooms. You may also use
the 8 major directions to link the rooms in the grid, as well as make
links to 'real' rooms from any point in the grid.

To show you how to do this, it's easiest to use an example. In the
directory ~malraux/vrtest there is a rather silly one to look over.


THE GRID DAEMON
---------------
The first item you need for a virtual room grid is a directory to place
the files in. Each grid needs a separate directory. Once you have that,
create a daemon.c in that directory that inherits VRDAEMON (you will 
have to #include <new_virtual.h> as well). The example daemon.c should
serve you well as a template. Set the variables in the file as needed:
  width - the east-west width of the area
  height - the north-south width of the area
  coord_dir - the directory where the daemon and its files are kept
  terrain - set this to set the terrain of all the rooms
  light - set this to 0 if you want all of your rooms to be lit. if
          it is set to 1, the daemon will expect you to map out the
          light values for the rooms (see below)
  numdescs - the number of descriptions your rooms will be using

  In daemon.c, you MUST call ::reset() after setting these values.
  ::reset() will load the database that you create for the rooms.
  Look at the example daemon, or just copy it, to do this right.


THE COORD.DESCS FILE
--------------------
Next, you need to create a file holding the descriptions of the rooms
in the grid. This file consists of a short and long description for
each separate description you want to have. Each must be one line long.
If you want to have a long desc longer than one line, put the desc in
a file with the extension .lf in the grid's directory. Then, on the
long desc line put #<filename without the .lf extension>#. For example,
look in the coord.descs file in the example directory. On line 2, you
see the reference to goomba.lf (I told you it was silly).

THE COORD.MAPPINGS FILE
-----------------------
After you have written the descriptions to use, you need to map them
onto the grid. That is, each grid point will reference a particular
description. If you have enough descriptions in your coord.descs file,
you can put one description per grid point.

The first section of coord.mappings consists of the description
mappings. For each grid point, you need to put the number of the
description that goes in that room. The descriptions are numbered
0 to numdescs-1, like an array (gee, I wonder where they're kept?).
I could have made it so you could number them 1 to numdescs, but
this makes it faster in execution. Woo, woo. The grid is oriented
with north at the top, and east to the right, like on a map. The 
numbering, however, is like pixels on a computer screen: 0,0 is in
the top lefthand corner, and x increases to the right while y
increases towards the bottom. The numbers must have one, and *only*
one space between them.

To take an example from the example rooms, the first line in the
coord.mappings file is 3 0 1. This means that room 0,0 will have
the 4th description in the coord.descs file, room 1,0 will have
the 1st desc, and room 2,0 will have the 2nd desc.

The next section of coord.mappings describes the exits of each point
on the grid. The exits are described in binary format, where each
of the exit directions has it's own bit in the number. To get the
exit descriptor for a room, add up the values of each exit direction.
The exit direction values are listed in /include/new_virtual.h, as
well as here:
North     -  1   South     -  2   East      -  4   West      -   8
Northeast - 16   Northwest - 32   Southeast - 64   Southwest - 128
So if you wanted a particular grid point to have north, south, and
northeast exits, you would add up 1, 2, and 16 to get an exit
descriptor of 19.

Taking the first line of exits from the coord.mappings file in the
example directory: 6 14 10, we find that room 0,0 has south and
east exits (2 + 4 = 6), room 1,0 has east, west, and south exits
(4 + 8 + 2 = 14), and room 2,0 has west and south exits (8 + 2 = 10).

To connect a virtual room to a real room, make a real room that
replaces one of the coordinates of the vr room.  In your daemon,
set up the 'rooms' var at that coordinate to point to the real
room's filename.  Look in the example daemon.c to see how this is
done.

The third section of the coord.mappings file is optional. If you 
decide that you want some of your rooms to be lit, and others not
lit, you need to use it. It consists merely of a grid, like the
desc and exit grids, with 1s and 0s to mark whether the grid point
is lit or not.


THE ENTRY POINT
---------------
Your grid area will need at least one entry point that is a normal room.
It needs to inherit VRROOM to interface with the grid. The entry room for
the example is, surprisingly enough, /u/m/malraux/ctest/entry.c. It 
inherits VRROOM and sets up a few necessary variables. The first is the
daemon that controls the grid room. Any exit to a normal room is done the
same as always, but an exit to a grid room should be a number. To get
this number, take the x coordinate of the destination grid room and
multiply by 100, then add the y coordinate to this. In other words,
make the grid coordinate into a number that looks like the coordinate
with the comma removed: 2,2 -> 02,02 -> 0202. You should note that
this implies that you may not have a grid area that is more than 100
rooms wide or deep.

NOTE: The above has changed. If your vrroom has a width or size greater
      than 100, the vrdaemon will instead use a size modulo of 1000.
      This means that your coordinates become 002002 in the above example.

